title: For Sale/Trade:  Collectors grade Norinco SKS
location: +\- 35 miles from Princeton IN, Evansville, Indiana
postcontent:
All matching Norinco Chinese sks. Sporter version. As can be seen in pic your typical sporter sks had a shortened barrel, bayonet lug removed, thumbhole stock and adapted to accept ak mags which redesigned the bolt carrier with no stripper clip slots. The sporter I am selling has a non thumbhole stock and does not accept ak mags.  Is full size barrel with bayonet and does use stripper clips for loading. It's 100% matching, original and real. Have green sling, cleaning kit that fits in stock, screwdriver type bayonet. Comes with between 400 rounds of various steel cased ammo.  I have owned for over 22 years. Less than 500 rounds shot thru it. Well taken care of and pristine condition. Again all numbers match. Is stamped Tucson AZ. Is also a legit DB stamp. Here's the history:

In 1989 sks were stamped sporter or sks-m to be allowed for import after a 1989 ban. These rifles were fitted with Monte Carlo or thumbhole stocks. Also made and adapted to accept ak mags. Also had the bayo lug removed. The rifle I have has had none of the cosmetic changes yet is stamped sporter. Plus it has the DB stamp. That means deport Bangladesh. Some Chinese made sks were stamped this or DP(Pakistan) or DK(Kampuchea). DP typically adds 10% value. DK about 15-20%. And the most rare DB adding up to 50% based on condition. Many DP have been forged to appear DB. They are easy to tell due to the mis proportion of the humps of the B. so the sporter mis-stamp, DB stamp and #'s matching drives it to a collectors rifle. 
And when I mention the 1989 ban I don't mean the 1994 awb. 

Also another change was the bolt carrier was changed on sporters with no slots for striped clips since they used ak removable mags and no stripper clip was needed. 
Most sporters had barrels shortened too.
